<DOC><DOCNO> AP890319-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 2351EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-SeaStallion-Glance     03-19 0161</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Sea Stallion-Glance,0171</SECOND><HEAD>The Sea Stallion Helicopter</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Korea-Copter Crash</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Sea Stallion helicopter that crashed in South Korea earlyMonday, killing 22 of the 37 Marines aboard, is one of a family ofheavy assault choppers with a reputation for good performance.   CAPACITY: 55 soldiers, or cargo, plus a crew of four.   DIMENSIONS: 67 feet, 2 inches long; 24 feet, 11 inches high.   WEIGHT: Empty, 23,485 pounds; loaded, 42,000 pounds.   RANGE: 540 miles.   TOP SPEED: 196 mph.   MANUFACTURER: Sikorsky Aircraft of Stratford, Conn.   HISTORY: First ordered by the Marine Corps in 1969 as a successorto the CH-53A, and used in the Vietnam War. An advanced version, theCH-53E Super Stallion began service in 1981.   The Navy, Coast Guard and Air Force also use versions of thehelicopter with differing model names and numbers. A similar model,the RH-53D Sea Stallion, was used in the abortive U.S. mission torescue American hostages held in Iran.</TEXT></DOC>